I included persuasive language to inspire other citizens to take action and vote for the
proposition. While the visuals may bring attention to the article and the descriptions may offer
details about the situation, none of this matters if votes are not cast for the proposition. As a
result, I was sure to add a call to action that brings the issue directly to the reader and specifically
asks them to make a difference with their vote.
The part of this project that I found most challenging was deciding what form I wanted
my advertisement to take. As Laura Bolin Carroll explained in “Backpacks vs. Briefcases: Steps
toward Rhetorical Analysis,” it is extremely important for writers to consider how their writing
will be perceived by their audience in designing it (Carroll 2010). In my first draft, I was unsure
whether I was going to create a poster or a brochure, but I knew I wanted to do one or the other
so that the ad could be easily distributed in community centers. Consequently, I ended up with a
suboptimal combination of the two, with too much text to be read at a glance but not enough
detail to be as informational as I had wanted. To solve this, I decided to commit to making a
poster as that is a more prominent way to display information, and I greatly reduced the number
of words in each paragraph to improve readability. Furthermore, I modified visuals so that a
quick glance gave enough information for readers to understand the issue and support the
proposition.
